{
  "texts": [
    "71 This issue is not exclusive to AI and has been addressed in various industries, such as pharmaceuticals and aviation.",
    "Over time, as consumers become more familiar with autonomous systems, their expectations can gradually align with the reality of these technologies (Garza, 2012, 601).",
    "When determining the expected safety level, courts have recognised that inherently dangerous products are not automatically considered defective.",
    "Producers must consider that the general public may not be aware of all the specific dangers associated with a product beyond the obvious ones and, therefore, cannot be expected to adjust their expectations accordingly 69 AI systems are particularly susceptible to \"tail effects,\" which refer to low-probability events that are difficult or impossible to train in the input data of deep learning models.",
    "These events pose a risk when AI systems perform tasks like navigation in unfamiliar environments or under new conditions (Veitch & Alsos, 2022, 2)."
  ]
}